        <div class="wrap">

            <!-- Introduction -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🏰 The Badgujar Rajput Legacy</h2>
                <p class="dropcap">The Badgujar Rajputs, a legendary warrior clan, have left an indelible mark on Indian history, particularly in the regions of Rajasthan and Madhya Pradesh. Tracing their lineage to <strong>Lava (Luv)</strong>, the elder son of Bhagwan Shri Ram, the Badgujars ruled over several kingdoms and princely states before India's independence in 1947. Known for their bravery, military prowess, and administrative acumen, the Badgujar Rajputs played a crucial role in shaping the history and culture of central India. Their legacy is not just a tale of kings and kingdoms but a story of resilience, honor, and cultural preservation.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Badgujar in MP -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>⚔️ Badgujar Rajputs in Madhya Pradesh</h2>
                <p>Madhya Pradesh was home to several prominent Badgujar Rajput estates, including:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Th. Dhabla Ghosi</strong> — The ancestral seat of our family</li>
                    <li>Th.Dabla Dheer</li>
                    <li>Th.Dadiya Khedi</li>
                    <li>Th.Kamalpur</li>
                    <li>Th.Sadhan Khedi</li>
                </ul>
                <p>One of the most significant branches of the Badgujar Rajputs in the region was the <strong>Raizada branch</strong>, which held a twelve-village estate in Vidisha, granted to Raja Raisingh Badgujar by the Marathas. The main branches of the Badgujar Rajputs in Madhya Pradesh were:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Bhojavat</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Dharmangaj</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Raizada</strong></li>
                </ul>
                <p>Each of these branches contributed to the region's governance and cultural heritage.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Dabla Ghosi Estate -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🏯 The Th.Dabla Ghosi Estate: A Symbol of Badgujar Legacy</h2>
                <p>One of the most notable Badgujar estates was <strong>Th. Dabla Ghosi</strong>, whose history is intertwined with the legacy of <strong>Raja Goga Dev of Rajgarh-Machadi</strong>. His second son, Bhojraj Ji, moved from Machadi to Banawad, where his descendants lived for five generations. The lineage of Dabla Ghosi is as follows:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rudra Ji → Desh Ji → Madanmal Ji → Gyan Sahay Ji → Khanderay Ji</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Khanderay Ji later moved from Banawad to Kotda in Kheechiwada, where his successors continued to rule. His descendants included Karn Singh Ji, Kumbha Ji, Dashraj Ji, Mohkam Singh Ji, Guman Singh Ji, Raghunath Singh Ji, and Achal Singh Ji.</p>
                <p>Achal Singh Ji had two sons, <strong>Govardhan Singh and Zorawar Singh</strong>. After the defeat of the Marathas by Lord Hastings in 1818, <strong>Dabla Ghosi was declared a guaranteed estate (garanti riyasat)</strong>. The estate received financial support from various rulers:</p>

                <table class="history-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr><th>Ruler</th><th>Annual Support (₹)</th></tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Sindhia</td><td>4,000</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Dewas</td><td>100</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bhopal Darbar</td><td>900</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <p>Additionally, they held a village under Gwalior state, yielding ₹1,050 in revenue. After Rao Govardhan Singh's demise in 1854, his son <strong>Rao Gopal Singh</strong> took over, followed by <strong>Rao Chand Singh</strong> as the ruler of Th. Dhabla Ghosi.</p>

                <h3>👑 The Successors of Th. Dhabla Ghosi</h3>
                <p>Rao Chand Singh had five sons:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rao Hanuvat Singh</li>
                    <li>Zorawar Singh</li>
                    <li><strong>Keshari Singh</strong></li>
                    <li>Hakim Singh</li>
                    <li>Hukam Singh</li>
                </ul>
                <p>When Rao Hanuvat Singh passed away childless, his nephew <strong>Tha.sa.Bhupendra Singh</strong>, the son of Keshari Singh, became the ruler of Th.Dhabla Ghosi. The family's influence extended to villages like Panda (Tehsil Shujalpur) and Babroda (near Thikana Umri, Guna district), showcasing their enduring legacy.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Suryavanshi Lineage Details -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>📜 Suryavanshi Badgujar Rajput Lineage Details</h2>
                <table class="history-table">
                    <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Category</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>Dynasty</td><td>Suryavansh</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>Gotra</td><td>Kashyap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>Ancestral Land</td><td>Ayodhya</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>Branch</td><td>Maradadhvani</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>Sutra</td><td>Katyayani</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>Guru</td><td>Vashishta</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>Veda</td><td>Yajurveda</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>River</td><td>Saryu</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Clan Goddess</td><td>Ashavari Mata</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Sword</td><td>Sakal (Vijayalakshmi)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>11</td><td>Flag Symbol</td><td>Panchayan</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>12</td><td>Sacred Tree</td><td>Ashoka</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>13</td><td>Worshipped Deity</td><td>Shri Sitaram Ji</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>14</td><td>Clan God</td><td>Neelkanth Mahadev Ji</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>15</td><td>Salutation</td><td>Jai Raghunath Ji</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <!-- Four Dhams & Eight Branches -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🕉️ Four Sacred Places (Dhams) of Badgujar Clan</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Machadi</strong> — The ancestral seat</li>
                    <li><strong>Devti</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Koleshwar</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Kakavadi</strong></li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🌿 Eight Branches of Badgujar Rajput Suryavansh Clan</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Rajora Badgujar</strong> (Rajoragrah)</li>
                    <li><strong>Sikarwar</strong> (Sikri)</li>
                    <li><strong>Khandara</strong> (Anupshahar, Bhodsi)</li>
                    <li><strong>Marad</strong> (Panipat, Karnel)</li>
                    <li><strong>Rayjada</strong> (Vidhisha, Bhenlsa)</li>
                    <li><strong>Munjwal</strong> (Samahda)</li>
                    <li><strong>Pokarna</strong> (Pokaran)</li>
                    <li><strong>Kannaujiya Badgujar</strong> (Surgaj, U.P.)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Role in Indian History -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>⚔️ The Role of the Badgujars in Indian History</h2>
                <p>The Badgujar Rajputs were not just rulers but also defenders of their land and culture. They played a pivotal role in resisting foreign invasions and maintaining regional stability during the reigns of the Marathas, Rajputs, and Mughals. Their military strategies and administrative skills ensured the prosperity of their territories, making them key players in the power dynamics of central and western India.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Cultural Contributions -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🎨 Cultural and Social Contributions</h2>
                <p>Beyond their military achievements, the Badgujar Rajputs made significant contributions to the cultural and social fabric of Madhya Pradesh. They built forts, palaces, and temples that stand as testaments to their architectural prowess. Their patronage of art, literature, and religious institutions helped preserve Rajputana traditions, which continue to influence the region's culture today.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Modern Legacy -->
            <div class="panel">
                <h2>🌟 The Modern Legacy of the Badgujar Rajputs</h2>
                <p>Today, the Badgujar Rajputs continue to honor their heritage while adapting to modern times. Many descendants are active in politics, administration, and social service, ensuring that the clan's legacy remains relevant. Historical estates like <strong>Th.Dhabla Ghosi</strong> serve as reminders of their glorious past, while cultural events and family records keep their traditions alive.</p>

                <div class="closing-quote">
                    <p>"Veer Bhogya Vasundhara" — The brave inherit the earth</p>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 8px; color: var(--smoke);">The Badgujar Rajputs of Madhya Pradesh have left an enduring legacy that transcends time. Their story is not just a chapter in Indian history but a testament to the enduring spirit of honor, courage, and resilience.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
